t I've heard so far is that the TI line is good and the MX line is not. Do you need a GEforce4 TI xxxx? Probably not there are no games to take advantage of it's features. I'd probably go with a GEForce 3 TI 500 and call it good.<br><br>A 1.6 ghz chip should be good for you. Will you need more in 2-3 years? Odds are good. I'm still running a 900 and have had no problems with any game i've tried to play. 512k ram is also probably more than enough right now, many operating systems probably can't use even that amount of ram efficiently anyway. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/bforgottentruthforeignlegion.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=shyl>Shyl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#5F9EA0>(4/16/02 4:56:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub10.ezboard.com/fforgottentruthforeignlegiongeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1050.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: GeForce4 worth it?</span><hr size=1> I have the G4 Ti 4600. Do I need it? No. There isn't a game out there that really takes advantage of it (City of Heroes will be the first MMOG to use it). Some of the newer games coming out in the end part of the year will take some advantage of it, but most companies are still programming for the lowest common card (VooDoo 3/4/5 &amp; GeForce 2).<br><br>Your best bet for the money if you want to get a good card and decent price (okay somewhat decent price) the GeForce3 Ti 500 is your best bet.<br><br>If you do decide to go for the G4 stay _FAR_ away from the MX line. The G2 Ultra gives you better performance and is just a little more expensive.<br><br>Shyl <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub10.ezboard.com/fforgottentruthforeignlegiongenera